hands_on_practices.problem:
A function $f: \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}$ is defined by the following piecewise formula:
$$
f(x) = \begin{cases}
    x^2 - 4x + a  \text{for } x \le 0 \\
    b \cos(x) - 2  \text{for } 0  x  \frac{\pi}{2} \\
    \sin(x) - ax  \text{for } x \ge \frac{\pi}{2}
\end{cases}
$$
where $a$ and $b$ are real constants. The arguments of the trigonometric functions are specified in radians.

Determine the unique values of the constants $a$ and $b$ that ensure the function $f(x)$ is continuous over the entire set of real numbers, $(-\infty, \infty)$. In your final answer, provide the value for $a$ first, followed by the value for $b$.
